Tariff Submitter: CPV Saddleback Ridge Wind, LLC FERC Tariff Program Name: FERC FPA Electric Tariff Tariff Title: Market-Based Rate Tariff Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: May 19, 2023 Tariff Record Title: Shared Facilities Agreement - CMP Option Code: A
Shared Facilities Agreement This Shared Facilities Agreement ("Agreement") is made and entered into as of the 19th day of September ("Effective Date") by and among Saddleback Ridge Wind, LLC, a Massachusetts limited liability company ("Saddleback"), and Canton Mountain Wind, LLC, a Massachusetts limited liability company ("Canton"). Saddleback and Canton may be individually referred to as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties". Capitalized terms not herein defined shall have the definitions set forth in the below referenced LGIA. RECITALS WHEREAS, Saddleback has developed the Saddleback Ridge Wind Project ("Saddleback Project") and has entered into a Large Generator Interconnection Agreement with ISO New England, Inc., and Central Maine Power Company ("CMP") effective September 25, 2013, as may be amended from time to time ("LGIA"); WHEREAS, the LGIA sets forth terms and conditions by which Saddleback is responsible for funding: (i) the Interconnecting Transmission Owner's Interconnection Facilities that were constructed by and are owned and operated by CMP and that are used by Saddleback to interconnect the Saddleback Project to the New England Transmission System, and (ii) the construction, ownership, and operation of Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities, including the Shared Facilities, that are owned by Saddleback to deliver its electric output to the Interconnecting Transmission Owner's Interconnection Facilities; WHEREAS, Canton is developing the Canton Mountain Wind Project ("Canton Project") and has entered into a Large Generator Interconnection Agreement with ISO New England, Inc. and CMP effective September 25, 2013, as may be amended from time to time ("Canton LGIA"); WHEREAS, the Canton Project will use the Shared Facilities portions of the Saddleback Project's Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities and the Parties desire to share the ownership and use of such Shared Facilities, each holding an undivided interest in the Shared Facilities as co-tenants pursuant to this Agreement (each of Canton and Saddleback may be referred to herein as a "Co-Tenant" and collectively as the "Co-Tenants"); WHEREAS, the Canton Project and the Saddleback Project (collectively referred to as "Projects" or individually as a "Co-Tenant Project") will be separately metered in accordance with Appendix A and Schedule D of their respective generator interconnection agreements; WHEREAS, each of the Co-Tenants desires to engage Saddleback as Shared Facilities Manager to provide day-to-day, routine operation and maintenance services for the Shared Facilities and Saddleback desires to provide such services for the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms hereof; and

WHEREAS, the Parties are not agreeing to provide any FERC-jurisdictional interconnection or transmission service to each other pursuant to this Agreement and rather shall receive such services as they may be provided from CMP and/or ISO New England, Inc. pursuant to separate interconnection agreements, as appropriate. NOW THEREFORE, for and in consideration of the mutual covenants, terms, and conditions set forth herein and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is herein acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: Any term not defined in this Agreement shall have the meaning provided in the LGIA or SGIA, as applicable. The Shared Facilities that are the subject of this Agreement are described on Exhibit B to this Agreement.
Section 1.
TERMS AND CONDITIONS Ownership of Shared Facilities
1.1. Transfer of Shared Facilities. Pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, Saddleback agrees to Transfer to Canton an Undivided Interest, as a tenant in common with Saddleback, in and to the Shared Facilities in an amount equal to 40% of the Shared Facilities, resulting in Saddleback retaining an Undivided Interest, as Tenants in Common with Canton of 60% of the Shared Facilities.
1.2. Bill of Sale. On the date which is the later of the Energization Date for Canton Project (as that term is defined in the Power Purchase Agreement) or the date FERC approves the disposition of the undivided interest in the Shared Facilities (defined below) , the Co?? Tenants will execute and deliver a Bill of Sale, substantially in the form attached as Exhibit A ("Bill of Sale"), pursuant to which the Co-Tenants will consummate the transfer of the Shared Facilities described above.(the "Transfer Effective Date"). Upon the Transfer Effective Date, the transfer of the Shared Facilities will vest in each of the Co-Tenants' ownership of the Shared Facilities in their respective percentages set forth in Section 1.1 above, together with a right of vehicular and pedestrian access to the Shared Facilities over that certain the real property described in a Deed to Saddleback from Linwood and Roxanne Worster, recorded in the Oxford County (East) Registry of Deeds in Book 4917, at Page 223, as affected by a certain deed from Saddleback to Central Maine Power Company recorded in said Registry in Book 4955, Page 151 and being the site upon which the Shared Facilities are located.
1.3. Conveyance; Condition of Property. EXCEPT AS OTHERWISE SET FORTH HEREIN, ALL CONVEYANCES AND TRANSFERS OF THE SHARED FACILITIES MADE PURSUANT TO THIS AGREEMENT ARE MADE "AS IS", "WITH ALL
Page 2 of 15 4828-5872-1847 5
FAULTS" AND WITHOUT WARRANTY, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING, WITHOUT LIMITATION, ANY WARRANTIES OF QUALITY MERCHANTABILITY, SUITABILITY AND FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, ANY WARRANTIES REGARDING THE EXISTENCE OF ANY SECURITY INTEREST, LIEN OR ENCUMBRANCE, AND ANY WARRANTIES ARISING BY COMMON LAW, EXCEPT THAT (A) EACH CO-TENANT REPRESENTS AND WARRANTS THAT IT HAS GOOD AND MARKETABLE TITLE TO THE SHARED FACILITIES AND THAT IT IS GRANTING AN INTEREST IN SUCH SHARED FACILITIES UNDER THIS AGREEMENT FREE AND CLEAR OF ALL LIENS, CLAIMS AND ENCUMBRANCES AND (B) EACH CO-TENANT REPRESENTS AND WARRANTS THAT IT HAS THE FULL POWER, RIGHT, AND AUTHORITY TO CONVEY ANY SHARED FACILITIES CONVEYED HEREUNDER.
1.4. Surrender and Assignment. A Co-Tenant who abandons or decommissions its Project shall convey its Undivided Interest and assign its rights hereunder to the other Co-Tenant at no cost or expense to the other Co-Tenant and, upon conveyance, cease to have any right, title or interest in its Undivided Interest (such Co-Tenant, a "Surrendering Co?? Tenant"). The Surrendering Co-Tenant must (a) deliver all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect the conveyance of its Undivided Interest and assignment of its rights hereunder to, and which are reasonably satisfactory to, the remaining Co-Tenant; (b) assign and convey to the remaining Co-Tenant all its rights under this Agreement, provided, however, that any such surrender of an encumbered Undivided Interest may also be surrendered upon (i) the written consent of each Secured Party that holds a security interest in such Undivided Interest and a release of such Secured Party's security interest being provided by such Secured Party; (ii) receipt of any necessary governmental approvals; and (c) cure of all Events of Default then existing on the part of the Surrendering Co-Tenant. The surrender of its Undivided Interest shall not relieve the Surrendering Co-Tenant of any of its obligations under this Agreement or any other agreement entered into pursuant to this Agreement, unless expressly provided for in this Agreement, or in a writing between the Co-Tenants. 1.5. No Interference. No Co-Tenant shall use or allow the use of the Shared Facilities that would create waste or nuisance that would have a material adverse effect on any or all of the Shared Facilities.
1.6. Term. The term of this Agreement ("Term") will commence on the Execution Date, and, unless sooner terminated by mutual agreement of all Parties, will continue as to each Co?? Tenant until the end of the commercial life of such Co-Tenant's Project and as to the Shared Facility Manager until it resigns or is removed in accordance with Section 2.2.
Page 3 of 15 4828-5872-1847.5
Section 2. Operation and Management
2.1. Interconnection Agreement Requirements. During the Term of this Agreement, the Shared Facilities Manager shall be the single point of contact with the Transmission Provider and the Transmission Owner as to all issues affecting the Shared Facilities. 2.2. Appointment. Removal and Replacement of Shared Facilities Manager. Saddleback is hereby appointed by the Co-Tenants as the initial Shared Facilities Manager. (a) The Shared Facilities Manager shall hold such position until it (i) resigns for convenience and without any liability to any of the Co-Tenants upon at least ninety (90) days prior written notice to the Co-Tenants, or (ii) is removed for cause in the event of any bad faith, gross negligence, recklessness or willful misconduct in connection with performance of its duties hereunder upon notice from either Co-Tenant. Notwithstanding the foregoing, should the Shared Facilities Manager (i) make an assignment for the benefit of creditors, (ii) file a petition or otherwise commence, authorize or acquiesce in the commencement of a proceeding under any bankruptcy or similar law for the protection of creditors, (iii) has such petition filed against it and such petition is not withdrawn or dismissed within sixty (6) days after such filing, (iv) becomes insolvent or, (v) is unable to pay debts when due ("Bankruptcy Event"), Shared Facilities Manager shall be removed immediately, without notice, and the obligations shall be assu .ed by the Canton Co-Tenant, or its qualified designee. (b) Upon any such resignation or removal, the Co-Tenants shall appoint by mutual agreement a new Shared Facilities Manager that is experienced and qualified to perform the duties of the Shared Facilities Manager set forth in this Agreement. 2.3. Maintenance of the Shared Facilities. The Shared Facilities Manager agrees to perform and provide with respect to the Shared Facilities professional, supervisory, managerial administrative and operational responsibilities in accordance with prudent industry practice. The Shared Facilities Manager shall be responsible for compliance with any NERC Reliability Standards applicable to the Shared Facilities. For the avoidance of doubt, each Co-Tenant shall be individually responsible for compliance with NERC Reliability Standards applicable to the Projects except with respect to the Shared Facilities. The Shared Facilities Manager shall prepare and submit to Co-Tenants annually a budget ("Budget") that shall contain a plan for expected and detailed cost estimates and activities for operation, repair and maintenance of the Shared Facilities. Each Co-Tenant shall have thirty (30) days to approve the Budget. If a Co-Tenant object to a portion of the Budget, the Co-Tenant must describe the dispute, in writing and all Parties shall discuss the matter in dispute and attempt to resolve it. If no agreement is reached prior to the commencement of the next annual period, the prior year's approved Budget will be used until the new Budget is approved.
Page 4 of 15 4828-5872-1847 5
2.4. Disconnection from Shared Facilities. (a) A Project shall be disconnected from the Shared Facilities if disconnection is necessary for safety in order to perform maintenance to any portion of the Shared Facilities or in the event of an Emergency Condition. No Co-Tenant shall be liable to any other Co-Tenant for lost production or revenue that occurs as a result of any disconnection or outage of the Shared Facilities in accordance with this Section 2.4. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Canton shall be liable to Saddleback for lost production or revenue that occurs as a result of a disconnection or outage of the Shared Facilities in order to interconnect the Canton Project to the Shared Facilities. (b) The Co-Tenants shall limit the length of any interruption or curtailment pursuant to this Section 2.4 to that time strictly nece sary to correct the problem or comply with the applicable Interconnection Agreement. Any interruption or curtailment pursuant to Section 2.4 shall be made only to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low energy prices and wind speeds so as to minimize potential loss of revenue of the Co-Tenants(s) being curtailed.
2.5. Specific Authority. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, and subject to the limitation of authority of the Shared Facilities Manager in Section 2.6 below or otherwise et forth in this Agreement, in addition to the authority otherwise granted herein, the Shared Facilities Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the other Co-Tenants, to do any of the following: (a) to negotiate, enter into on behalf of the Co-Tenant and administer agreements with third party contractors, or to employ persons, and to otherwise expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance, and repair of the Shared Facilities in accordance with this Agreement; provided, however, that (i) such engagement and any fees paid to such third party contractor thereunder shall be in accordance with the Approved Shared Facilities Budget, (ii) with respect to any agreement with a third party contractor that is an Affiliate of the Shared Facilities Manager, the Shared Facilities Manager enters into such agreement on an arms-length basis and with the prior written consent of all Co-Tenants, (iii) no such third party contractor engagement shall relieve the Shared Facilities Manager of its rights or obligations set forth in this Agreement, and (iv) any such agreements or other actions shall comply with all applicable financing documents; (b) to pay and collect on behalf of the Co-Tenants amounts due in connection with the Shared Facilities, but only in accordance with the approved Shared Facilities Budget; (c) to commit to the expenditure of, or spend, up to [One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000)] in the aggregate for and on behalf of the Co-Tenants to repair the Shared Facilities due to an Emergency Condition; provided that the Shared Facilities Manager gives concurrent notice, electronically and by phone, to the Co-Tenants regarding the nature and amount of the expenditure as soon as reasonably practicable after the
Page 5 of 15 4828-5872-1847 5
estimated amount of the expenditure is known by the Shared Facilities Manager, but in any event no later than at the time the Shared Facilities Manager commits to the expenditure; and
(d) to negotiate with, and represent the Co-Tenants' interests before, any Governmental Authority regarding property valuation and real property taxes (if any) related to Shared Facilities; provided that any agreements or settlements with respect to the foregoing are approved by the Co-Tenants. 2.6. Limitation on Authority. The Shared Facilities Manager shall not take any of the following actions without the prior written approval of all Co-Tenants with a beneficial interest affected by the action: (a) create or cause to be created any lien on any of the Shared Facilities; (b) amend or modify the terms of this Agreement, or any other agreement that affects any Co-Tenant's rights hereunder to develop, own and operate its Project; (c) sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of the Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest, or any components of the Shared Facilities; (d) borrow funds or otherwise incur indebtedness on behalf of a Co-Tenant; (e) commit to expenditures in excess of Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000) per calendar year for each Co-Tenant or One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000) per calendar year in the aggregate for and on behalf of the Co-Tenants except for repairs to the Shared Facilities due to an Emergency Condition; (f) incur an expense of more than FiftyThousand Dollars ($50,000) in any single instance or cumulative expenses of more than One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000) in the aggregate in any calendar year that is not included in the Approved Shared Facilities Budget; (g) adopt or amend or modify the approved Shared Facilities Budget; or (h) do any act that is specified as being beyond the authority of a Co-Tenant under this Agreement, or in contravention of, or that will otherwise cause a Co-Tenant to be in default under this Agreement. 2.7. Manager Fee. Shared Facilities Manager shall collect a fee for performing its services in an amount equal to $5,000 per year. Such fee shall be billed on an annual basi commencing on the Commercial Operation Date of the Canton Project.
Page 6 of 15 4828-5872-1847.5
2.8. Market Operations. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall be required to appoint a Market Participant, as such term i defined in the ISO-NE Tariff and that Market Participant shall be responsible for all schedule coordination and communication telemetry with the Transmission Owner and the Transmission Provider related to scheduling. (b) Nodes in the Transmission Provider's market model shall be established for each of the Projects and each Project will be responsible for offering its Project into the market, for settlement of cleared energy sales, and for responding separately to the Transmission Provider's dispatch instructions.
2.9. No Jurisdictional Service. The Co-Tenants acknowledge that none of the Co-Tenants are providing interconnection or transmission service, and rather that the Co-Tenants are receiving interconnection service under the Generator Interconnection Agreements, and that the Co?? Tenants can obtain transmission service, if desired, from the Transmission Owner and the Transmission Provider. Section 3. Shared Expenses
3.1. Responsibility for Shared Expenses. (a) Each Party shall be responsible for its pro-rata share of all expenses and liabilities relating to the use, maintenance, repair and inspection of the Shared Facilities. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for its share of any fees due to landowners relating to Shared Facilities. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall be solely responsible for the Interconnecting Transmission Owner's Interconnection Facilities and Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities other than the Shared Facilities identified on each Co-Tenant's Interconnection Agreement ("Sole Use Facilities").
(c) Canton shall not be responsible for Shared Expenses until Canton Project's Commercial Operation Date. 3.2. No later than ten (10) days after the end of each calendar month following the date on which Canton is obligated to make any payment under Section 3. l(c), Saddleback as Shared Facilities Manager shall invoice Canton for its share of the Shared Expenses described in Section 3. l(a), as well as any insurance, overhead, easement and other expenses incurred in connection with the ownership, operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities. Such invoice shall include a detailed breakdown of the expense and Canton's share of such expenses. Canton shall make all payments to Shared Facilities Manager as provided in the invoice within thirty (30) days of receipt of such invoice.
Page 7 of 15 4828-5872-18-17 5
3.3. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, each Party will develop, construct, operate and maintain its Project and perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with (a) all applicable laws, (b) prudent industry practices, (c) the LGIA or SGIA to which it is a party, (d) any and all governmental approvals, and (e) the applicable power purchase agreements to which it is a party. No Party will take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation that materially and adversely affects any other Party or its Project or gives rise to a liability affecting the other Party or its Project, including any action, omission or failure to perform an obligation that results in damage to, disconnection of, or an outage of, the other Party's Project, except that an outage or disconnection is permissible if necessary for: (i) the interconnection of the Canton Project and (ii) by either Party to perform maintenance or service of its Project. Section 4. Default and Remedies 4.1 Events of Default; Default. The following shall each constitute a default by a Co-Tenant under this Agreement (an "Event of Default"): (a) failure by a Co-Tenant to pay in full any amount due and payable hereunder when due where such failure is not cured within thirty (30) days after written notice of such failure; (b) A Co-Tenant (i) makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, (ii) files a petition or otherwise commence, authorize or acquiesce in the commencement of a proceeding under any bankruptcy or similar law for the protection of creditors, (iii) has such petition filed against it and such petition is not withdrawn or dismissed within sixty (6) days after such filing, (iv) becomes insolvent or, (v) is unable to pay debts when due ; (c) a representation or warranty made by a Co-Tenant under this Agreement was false or misleading in any material respect when made, where the material adverse effects of or relating to such representation or warranty are not cured within thirty (30) days after written notice thereof from the non-defaulting Co-Tenant; provided, that if such Co-Tenant has commenced and is diligently pursuing such cure and provides the other Co-Tenant with adequate assurance of due performance, the cure period shall be extended to not more than one hundred eighty (180) days after the written notice of default, as shall be necessary for such Co-Tenant to cure such material adverse effect with all due diligence and dispatch; and 4.2 Remedies. In addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or equity or under this Agreement (all of which will be cumulative), following an Event of Default: (a) The non-defaulting Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant's Secured Parties or other interest holders will be entitled following an Event of Default to perform the obligations of the defaulting Co-Tenant, and the defaulting Co-Tenant will reimburse the performing Co-Tenant for its expenses which it incurred in rendering the performance; (b) The Co-Tenants agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for an Event of Default under his Agreement, and that each Co-Tenant will be entitled to seek injunctive and
Page 8 of 15 4828-5872-1847 5
other equitable relief against the other Co-Tenant to prevent or eliminate such default, or to enforce the provisions of this Agreement. Section 5. Dispute Resolution. 5.1 Dispute Resolution and Procedures. (a) All disputes between or among any of the Co?? Tenants shall be resolved in accordance with the dispute resolution procedure set forth in this Article 5. Notwithstanding the foregoing, (a) any Co-Tenant may at any time seek injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction in accordance with Section 5. l(b) of this Agreement, and (b) nothing herein shall prevent any Co-Tenant from defending or pursuing any claim in a court or other proceeding against a third party. (b) Notice; Meeting and Confer. In the event a dispute arises regarding the application or interpretation of any provision of this Agreement, the Co-Tenant alleging the dispute shall promptly notify the other Co-Tenant of the dispute in writing. If the Co-Tenants fail to resolve the dispute within ten (10) days after delivery of such written notice, each Co?? Tenant shall, within five (5) days of receipt of a written demand from the other Co-Tenant to do so, di ??ect a member of its senior management to confer in good faith within five (5) days with a member of senior management of the other Co-Tenants to resolve the dispute. Should the Co?? Tenants be unable to resolve the dispute to their mutual satisfaction within fifteen (15) days, each Co-Tenant shall have the right to pursue any rights at law in equity. Section 6. Indemnity, Use and Compliance. 6.1 Indemnity. Each Party (an "Indemnifying Party") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Parties (an "Indemnified Party") and its Indemnitees from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees. which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Party or its Indemnitees or asserted against such Indemnified Party by any third Person in connection with (i) any negligent or willful acts, bad faith or reckless misconduct or any omissions (where such Indemnifying Party (or any of its directors, officers, partners, members, Affiliates, employees, agents, successors and assigns) has a legal or contractual duty to act) of or on behalf of the Indemnifying Party or its directors, officers, partners, members, Affiliates, employees, agents, successors and assigns, on or with respect to its Project Controlled Assets, (ii) the performance by the Indemnifying Party (or any of its directors, officers, partners, members, Affiliates, employees, agents, successors and assigns) of its duties and obligations under this Agreement, (iii) breach of the Indemnifying Party's obligations under this Agreement, and (iv) any other action by or on behalf of the Indemnifying Party (or any of its directors, officers, partners, members, Affiliates, employees, agents, successors and assigns) on the Shared Facilities located on the Project sites. Notwithstanding anything contained in this Agreement to the contrary, each Party's obligations under this Section 6.1 shall survive the expiration of the term of this Agreement or earlier termination of this Agreement; provided, however that any such obligation shall survive such expiration or earlier termination only to the extent that the event giving rise to a claim for indemnification under this Section 6.1 shall have arisen prior to such expiration or earlier termination.
Page 9 of 15 4828-5872-1847 5
6.2 Environmental Compliance. Without limiting the scope of each Party's obligations under Section 6.2 hereof, each Party shall, with respect to facilities that are not Shared Facilities, be responsible for all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any governmental authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters (for the avoidance of doubt, "environmental" matters include, but are not limited to, the protection of natural resources and wildlife) or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to such Party's use, operation or ownership of its Shared Facilities, except to the extent that such investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action are required in response to the actions, negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions of another Party in which case such other Party shall be responsible for all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action to the extent arising from its negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions. Each Party shall have the right (but not the obligation, unless otherwise required above) to participate in the management and control of all investigations and any environmental cleanup, remediation or related activities relating to its facilities that are not Shared Facilities. With respect to the Shared Facilities, the Shared Facilities Manager shall oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any governmental authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the Parties' use, operation or ownership of the Shared Facilities each Party shall be responsible, in proportion to its Undivided Interest, determined as of the date of the event resulting in any such investigation, environmental cleanup, corrective action or response or remedial action, for all liabilities related to such investigations, studies, clean-up, corrective action or response or remedial action, except to the extent that such investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action are required in response to the actions, negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions of a Party in which case such Party shall be responsible for all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action to the extent arising from its negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions. Each Party covenants and agrees to promptly provide a copy to each other Party of any written correspondence between it and any governmental authority with respect to environmental matters relating to the Shared Facilities or its facilities that are not Shared Facilities to the extent that it could reasonably be expected to materially and adversely affect the Shared Facilities or another Party's other facilities that are not Shared Facilities.
6.3 Taxes. Each Party shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Project or the facilities and fixtures located thereon. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment.
Page 10 of 15 4828-5872-1847 .5
6.4 Insurance. (i) Each Party shall, at all times during the term of this Agreement, procure and maintain, or cause to be procured and maintained, insurance against liability for injury to persons and/or property and death of any person or persons occurring, in, on or about the Shared Facilities in amounts and types of coverage consistent with prudent industry practice to the extent such insurance is reasonably available or obtainable on a commercially reasonable basis in the commercial insurance market. In addition, all insurance shall be primary insurance as to all claims thereunder and provide that any insurance carried by any other Person is excess and is non-contributing. (ii) Each Party shall name each other Parties as an additional insured with respect to any injury or damage arising from the presence or activities undertaken by such Party to the extent of the indemnity obligations assumed hereunder. Upon request, each Party shall furnish to the other Parties a certificate of insurance from its insurance carrier showing that the above required insurance is in full force and effect and the amount of the carrier's liability thereunder. Section 7. Force Majeure If performance of this Agreement or of any obligation hereunder is prevented or substantially restricted or interfered with by reason of an event of Force Majeure, the affected Party shall be excused from such performance to the extent of and for the duration of such Force Majeure event. The affected Party shall use diligent and commercially reasonable efforts to avoid or remove such causes of nonperformance and shall continue performance as soon as such causes are removed. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the affected Party shall not be relieved from its monetary obligations arising pursuant to this Agreement. Section 8. Miscellaneous 8.1 The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the Parties will be individual and not joint or collective, and no Party shall be responsible for the default of the other Party under this Agreement. It is not the intention of the Parties to create, nor will this Agreement be deemed to create, any partnership, agency, joint venture or trust, or to authorize any Party to act as an agent, servant or employee for the other Party. Each Party will remain solely responsible for the actions of its own employees. 8.2 EXCEPT IN CASES OF FRAUD OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT, NEITHER PARTY SHALL BE LIABLE FOR ANY PUNITIVE, EXEMPLARY, CONSEQUENTIAL OR SPECIAL DAMAGES THAT ARISE OUT OF, RELATE TO, OR ARE OTHERWISE ATTRIBUTABLE TO THIS AGREEMENT OR THE PERFORMANCE OR NON?? PERFORMANCE OF SERVICES OR OTHER DUTIES HEREUNDER. FOR AVOIDANCE OF DOUBT, LOST REVENUES FROM LOST PRODUCTION OR PRODUCTION RESULTING FROM AN OUTAGE, DISCONNECTION, OR DAMAGE TO A PROJECT SHALL NOT BE CONSIDERED CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES HEREUNDER, AND SHALL BE FULLY RECOVERABLE DAMAGES FOR ANY CLAIMS ARISING HEREUNDER.
Page 11 of 15 4828-5872-1847 5
8.3 To the full extent permitted by law, each Party agrees to indemnify, defend and hold harmless each other Party and its directors, managers, officers, shareholders, partners, members, affiliates, employees, agents, representatives, successors and assigns (collectively, the "Other Indemnified Parties"), from and against any and all liabilities, including any damage to or an outage of another Party's Project, to the extent arising out of or related to any breach of this Agreement by the indemnifying Party, any grossly negligent act or omission of the indemnifying Party, or any hazardous materials spilled, generated, released or introduced by the indemnifying Party. The indemnification provided under this Section 8.3 will not apply to the extent the liabilities are caused by the gross negligence or intentionally wrongful acts or omissions of any of the applicable Other Indemnified Parties. 8.4 This Agreement may not be assigned without the prior written consent of the other Party. 8.5 This Agreement may be executed in multiple counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original for all purposes and all of which will constitute a single instrument. Scanned signatures shall be deemed original and binding signatures. 8.6 Any term of this Agreement may only be waived, amended, or added as mutually agreed upon in writing and signed by the Parties. Any changes will be attached as an addendum to this Agreement.
8.7 If any term of this Agreement is found by a court of competent jurisdiction for any reason to be invalid or unenforceable, the rest of it remains in full effect.
8.8 This Agreement shall be governed by, and construed in accordance with the laws of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts without regard to such Commonwealth's choice of law provisions.
8.9 This Agreement shall supersede in its entirety the Substation Agreement dated November 14, 2014. [Signature Page Follows]

CPV SADDLEBACK RIDGE WIND, LLC FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF
1) Availability
Seller makes electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below.
2) Rates
All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
3) Other Terms and Conditions
All other terms and conditions for sales under this Tariff shall be established by agreement between Seller and purchaser.
4) Seller Category
Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northeast region, as defined in 18 CFR 35.36(a); Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Central, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions, as defined in 18 CFR 35.36(a).
5) Compliance with Commission Regulations
Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller???s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller???s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller???s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6) Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority
Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41, Part 101, and Part 141, except for section 141.15.; and received blanket approval under Part 34. Saddleback Ridge Wind, LLC, ER15-2534-000 (Nov. 10, 2015).
7) Ancillary Services
PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP.
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider???s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
8) Revisions
Seller may file revisions of this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of Seller to unilaterally file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission???s Rules and Regulations.
9) Effective Date
This Tariff shall become effective on the date specified by the Commission.
